<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41528293</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>06</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>06</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1532-656X</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>40</Volume><Issue>2</Issue><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Season>Mar-Apr</Season></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Journal of pediatric health care : official publication of National Association of Pediatric Nurse Associates &amp; Practitioners</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Pediatr Health Care</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Advanced Practice Provider Perceptions of the Pediatric Work Environment in the Postpandemic Era.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>267</StartPage><EndPage>277</EndPage><MedlinePgn>267-277</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.pedhc.2025.12.004</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0891-5245(25)00407-9</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="INTRODUCTION" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">The COVID-19 pandemic profoundly disrupted the pediatric advanced practice provider (APP) workforce, intensifying stressors, and highlighting the importance of work environments that support APP wellbeing and role satisfaction.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="PURPOSE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">This study aimed to describe pediatric APPs' organizational climate, structural empowerment, and psychological empowerment, and examine organizational commitment.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">A descriptive cross-sectional survey was conducted among APPs at three Midwestern pediatric health systems. Validated instruments measured organizational climate (NP-PCOCQ), structural empowerment (CWEQ-II), and psychological empowerment (Spreitzer Scale).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">Among 145 respondents, mean scores indicated high professional visibility, physician relations, and independent practice, but lower administrative relations. APPs identified a lack of formal power, information, and support. APPs reported strong role meaning but lack of perceived impact. There were high levels of organizational commitment.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSION" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">There is a need to promote administrative relationships, APP leadership roles, and policies that recognize APP contributions to health systems and patient outcomes.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2025 National Association of Pediatric Nurse Practitioners. Published by Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Beckmann</LastName><ForeName>Nicole</ForeName><Initials>N</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Nicole Beckmann, Director of Advanced Practice Research &amp; Education, Children's Minnesota, Minneapolis, MN. Electronic address: Nicole.beckmann@childrensmn.org.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Nickel</LastName><ForeName>Amanda</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Amanda Nickel, Senior Statistician and Alycia Johnson, Senior Director of Advance Practice Providers, Children's Minnesota, Minneapolis, MN.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Bushaw</LastName><ForeName>Andrea</ForeName><Initials>A</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Andrea Bushaw, Director of Clinical Transformation, Gillette Children's, St. Paul, MN.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>McCarthy</LastName><ForeName>Christina</ForeName><Initials>C</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Christina McCarthy, APP Supervisor Pediatric Heart Center, M Health Fairview Masonic Children's Hospital, Minneapolis, MN.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo